aking it OK? Please?<br><br>Why does the fact that some folks here think the gloves are &quot;crappy&quot; make the misappropriation of them OK (or at least less bad)? Does someone have to snatch and sell the Gleaming Breastplate of Massive Doom before it's 'really' wrong?<br><br>If anything, the fact that they were 'crappy' gloves makes it worse. There would have been a much smaller population of people who could use them, and those folks were in much greater need of an upgrade. The temptation factor is smaller, too - it apparently didn't take an amazingly nifty item to push him over the edge.<br><br>Is he really sorry? If he continues to profit from his misdeed, I would say &quot;no&quot;. How, again, does an apology recompense the folks who were cheated out of gloves they could use?<br><br>How about another option - He has to donate an equivalent item to be rolled for by the folks who should have gotten the gloves, if he can't produce the ones from the raid. Not something useless they can't use (no caster robes, for example). Hey, how about whatever gloves he has?<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Ellywig</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Harumpf. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uvesete.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Vesete</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/18/02 7:56:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2350.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Open raid NBG violators - can they be redeemed?</span><hr size=1> I would have to say that his mistake was due to ignorance. restitution for such a fault should be worked out between the raid leader and said offender. especially if this was the first mistake he/she has made like this.. posting this like this would be like a manager chewing out an employee in front of customers and then asking the customers what his punishment should be. now if it is his/her first offense I personally think the apology should suffice. if it becomes a pattern then ban them from the raids you hold. one mistake is not grounds for public slander. if he does it again then it would be resonable to assume that it wasnt an honest mistake. <br>I have yet to see a reply where anyone else has had a problem with this peticular individule. I may be reletively new to eq compared to most here but I am not new to disputes like this. anyone who has played tabletop games know what i am talking about. my personal repentance to a situation like this would be to assist with future a raid and refuse loot and assist with the funding of said event. but again. the offended party and the offender need to work out a suitable option that benifits both parties in that the offenders name is restored by a public post by the offended party after recompense of the offense by the offender has been made and the discussion should stop there as it can be detrimental to the name of the offender. now has anyone else had a problem with the offender before this. if not this should be a dead issue and left up to the two parties or guilds to settle. if i were the guild leader of the offender i would offer restitution to the runner up of the roll for the item possibly something from the guild vault if my council was in agreement. if they werent i would personally see to it and put the offender on probation. <br><br>thats my opinion anyway. <p>Vesete <BR>10th cycle BeastLord <BR>Vah Shir</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umosushi.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mosushi</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> 